---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import { Icon } from 'astro-icon/components';

const PLAUSIBLE_PUBLIC_DASHBOARD = 'https://plausible.io/consenttheater.org';
---
<Layout
  title="Public stats — ConsentTheater"
  description="Aggregate, anonymous, public visit stats for consenttheater.org. Hosted on Plausible (Hetzner, Germany). First-party only, opt-in, no IP storage, no cookies set by the tracker."
>
  <section class="mx-auto w-full max-w-3xl px-6 pt-10 pb-12">
    <div class="mb-6">
      <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground">
        Public stats
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-1 font-display text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-3xl">
        How this site is used — out in the open
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
        Most websites that collect analytics keep them locked behind a Google
        account. We don't see the appeal: this is a non-commercial open-source
        project, the data is already aggregate and anonymous, so we publish it.
        The dashboard below lives on Plausible's own domain — go look, it's the
        same data we see.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-10 text-sm leading-relaxed text-foreground/90">

      <section id="dashboard">
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Live dashboard</h2>
        <p class="mb-4 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
          Hosted on Plausible. No login, no cookie required to view. Updates in real time.
        </p>
        <a
          href={PLAUSIBLE_PUBLIC_DASHBOARD}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="group flex w-full items-center justify-between gap-4 border border-border bg-card px-5 py-4 text-left transition-colors hover:bg-secondary"
        >
          <div class="min-w-0">
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground">
              Open dashboard
            </p>
            <p class="mt-1 truncate font-mono text-sm text-foreground/90">
              plausible.io/consenttheater.org
            </p>
          </div>
          <Icon
            name="ph:arrow-square-out"
            class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-muted-foreground transition-transform group-hover:translate-x-0.5"
            aria-hidden="true"
          />
        </a>
      </section>

      <section id="what-we-collect">
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">What we collect</h2>
        <p class="mb-3">
          When (and only when) you've explicitly accepted analytics through our
          <button
            type="button"
            data-action="open-consent"
            class="link cursor-pointer bg-transparent p-0 underline-offset-2 hover:underline"
          >consent banner</button>,
          your browser sends a single pageview event directly to
          <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">plausible.io/api/event</code>.
          No event is sent to ConsentTheater servers — Plausible is the only
          recipient. Each event records:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-1.5 pl-6">
          <li>The page URL you're on (e.g. <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">/methodology/</code>)</li>
          <li>Referrer (so Plausible can show entry sources, e.g. <em>Hacker News</em>)</li>
          <li>Country, derived from your IP at request time by Plausible's ingestion server — IP is never stored</li>
          <li>Device type (mobile / tablet / desktop) and browser, derived from your User-Agent</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Plausible processes the event and discards the IP without storing it.
          Aggregate counts land in their database in
          <strong>Hetzner Falkenstein, Germany</strong>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="what-we-dont-collect">
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">What we don't collect</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-1.5 pl-6">
          <li><strong>No personal data.</strong> No name, no email, no account.</li>
          <li><strong>No IP storage.</strong> Country is derived in flight by Plausible's server; the IP is discarded immediately.</li>
          <li><strong>No cookies set by the tracker.</strong> Plausible does not set any cookie at all.</li>
          <li><strong>No cross-site identifiers, no fingerprinting.</strong> Same visitor on two visits looks like two different visits.</li>
          <li><strong>No third-party script loaded in your browser.</strong> The Plausible tracker is bundled into our own JavaScript from the official open-source npm package — your browser never fetches anything from Plausible's CDN.</li>
          <li><strong>No advertising tracking</strong>, ever. There are no ad-tech toggles to flip — those technologies aren't on this site at all.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="why-public">
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Why public</h2>
        <p>
          This project audits other people's privacy practices. The least we can do
          is run our own analytics in glass. Three concrete reasons:
        </p>
        <ol class="mt-3 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-6">
          <li>
            <strong>Accountability.</strong> Anyone can verify what we said in the
            consent banner against what the dashboard actually shows. If we ever
            drift, the public record makes it obvious.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Useful research signal.</strong> If a regulator or journalist
            wants to know how cookie-consent topics are trending in attention, our
            traffic pattern is a small but honest data point — and they don't need
            to ask permission to look.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Dogfooding.</strong> Our methodology argues that aggregate,
            consent-gated, no-third-party analytics is fine under GDPR. It's only
            credible if we run our own site that way.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section id="why-plausible">
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Why Plausible</h2>
        <p>
          We weighed pros and cons and decided analytics should live on
          privacy-friendly European servers, not on US infrastructure. Plausible
          checks every box we care about: open-source (AGPL), EU-incorporated
          (Estonia) and EU-hosted (Hetzner, Germany), no cookies by design, no
          fingerprinting, full GDPR / ePrivacy compliance posture documented in
          public, and an explicit "no IP storage" guarantee.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          We use their official npm package, so the tracker code ships with our
          own JavaScript — no third-party script is loaded from plausible.io into
          your browser. The only network call is the consent-gated POST to
          <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">plausible.io/api/event</code>,
          and only after you have explicitly accepted.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="how-to-opt-out">
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">How to opt in or out</h2>
        <p>
          Analytics is <strong>off by default</strong>. To toggle:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-1.5 pl-6">
          <li>
            Open the
            <button
              type="button"
              data-action="open-consent"
              class="link cursor-pointer bg-transparent p-0 underline-offset-2 hover:underline"
            >consent banner</button>
            from the footer of any page (the "Cookie preferences" link).
          </li>
          <li>
            Pick <em>Accept analytics</em> or <em>Reject analytics</em>. Your
            choice is stored in a cookie called
            <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">zest_consent</code>
            for 365 days.
          </li>
          <li>
            Browsers sending <strong>Do Not Track</strong> or <strong>Global Privacy
            Control</strong> are treated as a default <em>reject</em>. You can still
            override that through the banner if you want.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          For the technical specifics — every cookie, every storage entry, every
          permission — see <a href="/privacy/" class="link">the privacy policy</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
